<subSubSection id="99E164251D539B97141DD862F4731DE4" pageId="0" pageNumber="1023" type="taxon discussion">
<paragraph id="B548BA02DF68EA505C66DA9242FFD261" pageId="0" pageNumber="1023">Taxon discussion</paragraph>
<paragraph id="B381BF269AFF1694B3F5604172C809C5" pageId="0" pageNumber="1023">
<taxonomicName id="6E0FB343C30909D18ED8E4B0C3088197" class="Insecta" family="Hesperinidae" genus="Hesperinus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Hesperinus ninae" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1023" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ninae">Hesperinus ninae</taxonomicName>
(Figs 2, 3) was described from two male specimens collected in the 1960s from Krasnaya Polyana (Krasnodar Kray in Russian North Caucasus), but according to Papp &amp; Krivosheina (
<bibRefCitation id="FB90123F27156CCA37070A52376E2315" author="Papp, L." journalOrPublisher="Russian Entomological Journal" pageId="0" pageNumber="1023" pagination="293 - 297" title="Description of a new species of Hesperinus Walker, 1848 from the North Caucasus (Diptera: Hesperinidae)" volume="18" year="2010">Papp and Krivosheina 2010</bibRefCitation>
) other material from the same collecting series had already been included in an overview by Mohrig et al. (
<bibRefCitation id="976578B55D3908313F611D3C2524F6CD" author="Mohrig, W." journalOrPublisher="Zoologischer Anzeiger" pageId="0" pageNumber="1023" pagination="339 - 344" title="Zur Kenntnis fluegelreduzierter Dipteren der Bodenstreu. VII. Beitrag. Gattung Hesperinus (Diptera, Hesperinidae)" volume="194" year="1975">Mohrig et al. 1975</bibRefCitation>
: as 
<taxonomicName id="A96E83A8B1ABAAC4AB0801A487312164" class="Insecta" family="Hesperinidae" genus="Hesperinus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Hesperinus imbecillus" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1023" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="imbecillus">Hesperinus imbecillus</taxonomicName>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="CA493F1478C5D387A5790B3A4861A02D" pageId="0" pageNumber="1023">
Using the key by Papp (
<bibRefCitation id="6B8E42924C7388AE461AE83972E0FEB3" author="Papp, L." journalOrPublisher="Acta Zoologica Academiae Scientiarum Hungaricae" pageId="0" pageNumber="1023" pagination="347 - 370" title="A study on Hesperinus Walker with description of a new species (Diptera: Hesperinidae)" volume="56" year="2010">Papp 2010</bibRefCitation>
), the studied specimens run well to 
<taxonomicName id="75EBE59A4F02D618381070845F4C866A" class="Insecta" family="Hesperinidae" genus="Hesperinus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Hesperinus ninae" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1023" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ninae">Hesperinus ninae</taxonomicName>
because of the elongated terminal flagellomere (Fig. 2c), wing length about 6 mm (Fig. 2b), considerably shorter and broader first flagellomere with specific setation (Fig. 2d), and gonostylus mediodorsally with a projecting lobe (Fig. 3c). Like the European 
<taxonomicName id="7D8EE55F62C1AE0D7A40BC7C9B597201" class="Insecta" family="Hesperinidae" genus="Hesperinus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Hesperinus imbecillus" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1023" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="imbecillus">Hesperinus imbecillus</taxonomicName>
, the females of 
<taxonomicName id="1B13C1DF969044B716B1E5CC40A901DB" class="Insecta" family="Hesperinidae" genus="Hesperinus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Hesperinus ninae" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1023" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ninae">Hesperinus ninae</taxonomicName>
are flightless. In spite, that there were no females included to the original description (
<bibRefCitation id="79472E5B48B33E3B1941AFE89180C489" author="Papp, L." journalOrPublisher="Russian Entomological Journal" pageId="0" pageNumber="1023" pagination="293 - 297" title="Description of a new species of Hesperinus Walker, 1848 from the North Caucasus (Diptera: Hesperinidae)" volume="18" year="2010">Papp and Krivosheina 2010</bibRefCitation>
), four of them from the same collecting series were studied by Mohrig et al. (
<bibRefCitation id="1A8C337BAFD7188ED82C966E04A9B334" author="Mohrig, W." journalOrPublisher="Zoologischer Anzeiger" pageId="0" pageNumber="1023" pagination="339 - 344" title="Zur Kenntnis fluegelreduzierter Dipteren der Bodenstreu. VII. Beitrag. Gattung Hesperinus (Diptera, Hesperinidae)" volume="194" year="1975">Mohrig et al. 1975</bibRefCitation>
, as 
<taxonomicName id="76E76152E415F8FEF81789829FABBD89" class="Insecta" family="Hesperinidae" genus="Hesperinus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Hesperinus imbecillus" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1023" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="imbecillus">Hesperinus imbecillus</taxonomicName>
). They figured a female with reduced wings (
<bibRefCitation id="FD394AE1770977D7226B8F20B631BD4C" author="Mohrig, W." journalOrPublisher="Zoologischer Anzeiger" pageId="0" pageNumber="1023" pagination="339 - 344" title="Zur Kenntnis fluegelreduzierter Dipteren der Bodenstreu. VII. Beitrag. Gattung Hesperinus (Diptera, Hesperinidae)" volume="194" year="1975">Mohrig et al. 1975</bibRefCitation>
: fig. 1) and did not described any differences between Northern Caucasian and Central European material (see also discussion by 
<bibRefCitation id="87AFF7C9FC8F4290F442E658356936F4" author="Papp, L." journalOrPublisher="Russian Entomological Journal" pageId="0" pageNumber="1023" pagination="293 - 297" title="Description of a new species of Hesperinus Walker, 1848 from the North Caucasus (Diptera: Hesperinidae)" volume="18" year="2010">Papp and Krivosheina 2010</bibRefCitation>
). The flightlessness has obviously been an adaptive response to unfavourable climatic conditions and has set further limits to dispersal. However, the current record is at quite a remote distance from the type locality, indicating that the species probably has a wide distribution in suitable habitats in the Caucasus.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
